註拙ｺTitle: title: Direnv
Path: Direnv
Content:
Many people use 
[link: https://direnv.net] direnv
 to load an environment when entering a directory and unload it when exiting the directory.
麟Iarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/cookbook/direnv.mdﾙ@c03bd1dfce1b492afc0b763185167b2475ee89f01675c4c9f3e55c542c298552ｭtitle: Direnv族How direnv worksﾚsFrom 
[link: https://direnv.net] direnv.net
:
Before each prompt, direnv checks for the existence of a 
``.envrc``
 file (and optionally a 
``.env``
 file) in the current and parent directories. If the file exists (and is authorized), it is loaded into a bash sub-shell and all exported variables are then captured by direnv and then made available to the current shell.
註接ｨTitle: title: Direnv
Path: How direnv works
Content:
From 
[link: https://direnv.net] direnv.net
:
Before each prompt, direnv checks for the existence of a 
``.envrc``
 file (and optionally a 
``.env``
 file) in the current and parent directories. If the file exists (and is authorized), it is loaded into a bash sub-shell and all exported variables are then captured by direnv and then made available to the current shell.
麟Iarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/cookbook/direnv.mdﾙ@a1ab6e14d77bfadd65506f8146a17565c86349d44b3aafa5e55bc7da6b0de2f6ｭtitle: Direnv多Configuring direnv in Nushellﾚ®n Nushell, it's possible to run direnv each time the prompt displays (using a 
[link: /book/hooks.html] ``pre_prompt``
 hook
). However, it's more efficient to update only when the directory is changed using an 
``env_change``
 hook along with:
[link: /commands/docs/from_json.md] ``from json``
 to convert the direnv output to structured data
[link: /commands/docs/load-env.md] ``load-env``
An 
``env-conversion``
 helper for the 
``PATH``
 from the 
[link: /book/standard_library.md] Standard Library
::: note
The direnv configuration below requires Nushell 0.104 or later.
:::
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
use std/config *

# Initialize the PWD hook as an empty list if it doesn't exist
$env.config.hooks.env_change.PWD = $env.config.hooks.env_change.PWD? | default []

$env.config.hooks.env_change.PWD ++= [{||
  if (which direnv | is-empty) {
    # If direnv isn't installed, do nothing
    return
  }

  direnv export json | from json | default {} | load-env
  # If direnv changes the PATH, it will become a string and we need to re-convert it to a list
  $env.PATH = do (env-conversions).path.from_string $env.PATH
}]

```
As with other configuration changes, this can be made permanent by adding it to your startup 
[link: /book/configuration.md] configuration
.
With this in place, direnv will now add/remove environment variables when entering/leaving a directory with an 
``.envrc``
 or 
``.env``
 file.
註接ﾇTitle: title: Direnv
Path: Configuring direnv in Nushell
Content:
In Nushell, it's possible to run direnv each time the prompt displays (using a 
[link: /book/hooks.html] ``pre_prompt``
 hook
). However, it's more efficient to update only when the directory is changed using an 
``env_change``
 hook along with:
[link: /commands/docs/from_json.md] ``from json``
 to convert the direnv output to structured data
[link: /commands/docs/load-env.md] ``load-env``
An 
``env-conversion``
 helper for the 
``PATH``
 from the 
[link: /book/standard_library.md] Standard Library
::: note
The direnv configuration below requires Nushell 0.104 or later.
:::
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
use std/config *

# Initialize the PWD hook as an empty list if it doesn't exist
$env.config.hooks.env_change.PWD = $env.config.hooks.env_change.PWD? | default []

$env.config.hooks.env_change.PWD ++= [{||
  if (which direnv | is-empty) {
    # If direnv isn't installed, do nothing
    return
  }

  direnv export json | from json | default {} | load-env
  # If direnv changes the PATH, it will become a string and we need to re-convert it to a list
  $env.PATH = do (env-conversions).path.from_string $env.PATH
}]

```
As with other configuration changes, this can be made permanent by adding it to your startup 
[link: /book/configuration.md] configuration
.
With this in place, direnv will now add/remove environment variables when entering/leaving a directory with an 
``.envrc``
 or 
``.env``
 file.
